      "solution": "import sys\n\n# 1. Read Inputs\ntry:\n    line1 = sys.stdin.readline().split()\n    if not line1: exit()\n    W = int(line1[0])\n    H = int(line1[1])\n    \n    line2 = sys.stdin.readline().strip()\n    K = int(line2)\n    \n    grid = []\n    for _ in range(H):\n        grid.append(list(sys.stdin.readline().strip()))\nexcept ValueError:\n    exit()\n\n# 2. Create Shadow Map\n# True = Shaded, False = Sunny\nshaded = [[False for _ in range(W)] for _ in range(H)]\n\n# 3. Cast Shadows\nfor r in range(H):\n    for c in range(W):\n        cell = grid[r][c]\n        # Check if it is an obstacle\n        if '1' <= cell <= '9':\n            height = int(cell)\n            shadow_len = height * K\n            \n            # Shadow projects North (upwards: r decreases)\n            for i in range(1, shadow_len + 1):\n                target_r = r - i\n                if target_r >= 0:\n                    shaded[target_r][c] = True\n\n# 4. Calculate Power\ntotal_power = 0\nfor r in range(H):\n    for c in range(W):\n        if grid[r][c] == 'P':\n            if not shaded[r][c]:\n                total_power += 100\n\nprint(total_power)",
      "statement": "Calculate the total power output of a solar roof by simulating vertical shadows.\n\nThe roof is represented as a grid of width [[W]] and height [[H]]. The sun is positioned at the <<bottom>> (South) of the map and shines towards the <<top>> (North).\n\nYou need to calculate how much power the solar panels {{P}} produce, considering that obstacles ({{1}}-{{9}}) cast shadows.\n\n<<Shadow Rules:>>\n\nObstacles cast shadows vertically towards the <<top>> (North).\n\nThe length of a shadow is determined by the formula: <<Length>> = <<Obstacle height>> × [[K]] (shadow coefficient).\n\nA shadow covers the <<Length>> cells directly above the obstacle.\n\n<<Power Rules:>>\n\nEach unshaded Solar Panel {{P}} produces {{100}} Watts.\n\nAny panel covered by a shadow produces {{0}} Watts.\n\nObstacles themselves do not produce power.",
